<subsection xml:id="tkLogarithms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title>Logarithms</title>
                 
<subsubsection xml:id="tkRadtoPowr"><title>Convert between radicals and powers</title>

<p>Because a logarithm is an exponent, it will be helpful to convert easily between radical notation and exponent notation.</p>

<example><statement><p>Write each power as a radical. 
<ol marker="a" cols="2">
    <li><m>x^{2/3}</m></li>
    <li><m>t^{-3/2}</m></li>
    <li><m>w^{1.25}</m></li>
    <li><m>z^{-0.4}</m></li>
</ol></p></statement>
 
<solution><p>Recall that the numerator of the exponent is the power and the denominator is the root.  A negative exponent indicates a reciprocal.
<ol marker="a">
    <li><m>x^{2/3} = \sqrt[3]{x^2}</m></li>
    <li><m>t^{-3/2} = \dfrac{1}{t^{3/2}} = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{t^3}}</m></li>
    <li><m>w^{1.25} = w^{5/4} = \sqrt[4]{w^5}</m></li>
    <li><m>z^{-0.4} = \dfrac{1}{z^{4/10}} = \dfrac{1}{z^{2/5}} = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt[5]{z^2}}</m></li>
</ol></p></solution></example>

<example><statement><p> Write each radical expression in exponential form and simplify.
<ol marker="a" cols="2">
    <li><m>\sqrt[4]{b^3}</m></li>
    <li><m>\dfrac{1}{\sqrt[6]{a^3}}</m></li>
    <li><m>x^2\sqrt[4]{x}</m></li>
    <li><m>\dfrac{\sqrt[3]{v}}{\sqrt{v}}</m></li>
</ol></p></statement>
 
<solution><p><ol marker="a">
    <li><m>\sqrt[4]{b^3} = b^{3/4}</m></li>
    <li><m>\dfrac{1}{\sqrt[6]{a^3}} = \dfrac{1}{a^{3/6}} = a^{-3/6} = a^{-1/2}</m></li>
    <li><m>x^2\sqrt[4]{x} = x^2x^{1/4} = a^{2+1/4} = a^{9/4}</m></li>
    <li><m>\dfrac{\sqrt[3]{v}}{\sqrt{v}} = \dfrac{v^{1/3}}{v^{1/2}} = v^{1/3-1/2} = v^{-1/6}</m></li>
</ol></p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><p>Write each power as a radical. 
<ol marker="a" cols="3">
    <li><m>m^{-3/5}</m></li>
    <li><m>p^{2.75}</m></li>
    <li><m>x^{0.18}</m></li>
</ol></p></statement>
    <answer><p><ol marker="a">
        <li><m>\dfrac{1}{\sqrt[5]{m^3}}</m></li>
        <li><m>\sqrt[4]{p^{11}}</m></li>
        <li><m>\sqrt[50]{x^{9}}</m></li>
</ol></p></answer></exercise>

<exercise><statement><p> Write each radical expression in exponential form and simplify.
<ol marker="a" cols="3">
    <li><m>\sqrt[10]{n^9}</m></li>
    <li><m>\sqrt{h}\sqrt[4]{h}</m></li>
    <li><m>\left(\sqrt[3]{t^2}\right)^4</m></li>
</ol></p></statement>
    <answer><p><ol marker="a">
        <li><m>n^{9/10}</m></li>
        <li><m>h^{3/4}</m></li>
        <li><m>t^{8/3}</m></li>
</ol></p></answer></exercise>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="tkEstLogs"><title>Estimate logs</title>

<p>It is useful to be able to estimate mentally the value of a log.</p>
                    
<example><statement><p>Write each log equation in exponential form. Then use trial and error to estimate the log between two integers.<ol marker="a" cols="2">
        <li><m>\log_2 {(6)}=x</m></li>
        <li><m>\log_2 {(24)}=x</m></li>
        <li><m>\log_2 {(100)}=x</m></li>
        <li><m>\log_2 {(0.3)}=x</m></li>
</ol></p></statement>

<solution><p><ol marker="a">
    <li><m>2^x=6.~</m> Because <m>~2^2=4~</m> and <m>~2^3=8</m>, <m>~2 \lt x \lt 3</m>.</li>
    <li><m>2^x=24.~</m> Because <m>~2^4=16~</m> and <m>~2^5=32</m>, <m>~4 \lt x \lt 5</m>.</li> 
    <li><m>2^x=100.~</m> Because <m>~2^6=64~</m> and <m>~2^7=128</m>, <m>~6 \lt x \lt 7</m>.</li> 
    <li><m>2^x=0.3.~</m> Because <m>~2^{-2}=\dfrac{1}{4} = 0.25~</m> and <m>~2^{-1}=\dfrac{1}{2} = 0.5</m>, <m>~-2 \lt x \lt -1</m>.</li>
</ol></p></solution></example>

