<subsubsection xml:id="tkUseLog"><title>Using logs</title>

<example><statement><p>Solve each exponential equation by writing your answer as a logarithm, then evaluate if possible (without a calculator).
<ol marker="a" cols="2">
    <li><m>3 \cdot 2^x = 96</m></li>
    <li><m>3 \cdot 2^x = 90</m></li>
</ol></p></statement>

<solution><p><ol marker="a">
    <li><p>First isolate the power to get <m>2^x = 32</m>. Then convert to logarithmic form as <m>x = \log_2{(32)}</m>. Because <m>2^5 = 32</m>, we can simplify the answer to <m>x = 5</m>.</p></li>
    <li><p>First isolate the power to get <m>2^x = 30</m>. Then convert to logarithmic form as <m>x = \log_2{(30)}</m>. This log is not easy to evaluate without a calculator.</p></li>
</ol></p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><p>Solve each exponential equation by writing your answer as a logarithm, then evaluate if possible (without a calculator).
<ol marker="a" cols="2">
    <li><m>2 \cdot 5^x - 20 = 230</m></li>
    <li><m>2 \cdot 5^x - 20 = 200</m></li>
    <li><m>3^x = 81</m></li>
    <li><m>3^{2x-5} = 81</m></li>
    <li><m>10^{2x} = 1000</m></li>
    <li><m>10^{2x} = 1200</m></li>
    <li><m>5 + 4^{3x} = 7</m></li>
    <li><m>5 + 4^{3x} = 8</m></li>
</ol></p></statement>

<answer><p><ol marker="a">
    <li><m>\log_5{(125)} = 3</m></li>
    <li><m>\log_5{(110)}</m></li>
    <li><m>\log_3{(81)} = 4</m></li>
    <li><m>\dfrac{1}{2}[5 + \log_3{(81)}] = \dfrac{9}{2}</m></li>
    <li><m>\dfrac{1}{3}\log_4{(2)} = \dfrac{1}{6}</m></li>
    <li><m>\dfrac{1}{3}\log_4{(3)}</m></li>
</ol></p></answer></exercise>

